metadata.name: Kintsugi #91
metadata.description:
Kintsugi is a philosophy, it's the concept of highlighting imperfections, visualizing patches and seams on the area to focus on, rather than focusing on missing details.

This art of precious scars is a technique used as a means of analyzing the idea of ‚Äã‚Äãloss through synthesis and restoration of the destroyed and a metaphor for the possibility of rebirth.
Recovery from destructive events is possible through care and patching, not through hiding the damage, but by accepting a new state of the object or the whole life.
The world is a vase that is endlessly disassembled and sewn together again, continuing to bear traces of each event.

Non-human entities helped us put these vases together. In the beginning, there were vague forms, these were the shards themselves, created in collaboration with Latent Diffusion. Over time, they have grown in detail, drawing their stories more clearly, thanks to Jax Diffusion.

The code that puts everything together was written by Yulikolay, for which he is greatly appreciated.

metadata.name: Canyon #109
metadata.description:
Canyon is a generative art project inspired by canyons and reinterpreted in 9 different styles (that each have their own specificities):
- Grand Canyon
- Radioactive
- Blue Grotto
- Black Crystals
- Magma
- Iceberg
- Imagination

Accessories (Kayak, Rowing Boat, Barrels) are present on some variations (in this case, it is possible to generate a second variation without accessories by pressing "a").

metadata.name: Missingno #275
metadata.description:
Containment has been breached and Missingno is on the loose. 
This unique beast doesn‚Äôt have a fixed shape and its appearance is ever-changing. 
Some call it a bug, very few know what it is truly made of.

Only now with present technology we managed to capture a fraction of its unlimited possible faces. 

Mint for a unique picture of Missingno, yet outdated the very moment it‚Äôs taken.


(Open live and click on the image to export)

metadata.name: Colored Elementary Cellular Automaton #437
metadata.description:
The algorithm is based on Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton. 
This is a 1D cellular automaton with a neighborhood of 5 cells. This gives us 2^5 = 32 patterns for a neighborhood and 2^32 = 4.29B possible combinations!!! The size of the cell varies in a range of 2 to 8. There is a 15% of getting a black and white art.

Pattern rarity:
- Pattern 1 _25%
- Pattern 2 _30%
- Pattern 3 _35%
- Pattern 4 _15%

Note: The art might look in different resolutions because of the responsive view, but the color, pattern, and layout remain the same.

metadata.name: musical society #594
metadata.description:
society.png: musical society is a collaborative PFP work drawn by Tito Yusuf and directed by Sandy Pirouzi with the aim to facilitate Tezos newcomers with affordable PFP to rock.

This series is taking inspiration from a music scene that Tito is part of. Some traits are paying tribute to some of Tezos musicians such as Jburn, Musical Jackal, Binerica, and Sigmun.

---------------------------------------------
‚Ä®‚Ä®Most will be us
Some are pretending to be us
Some others are even not us
(And few of them are not even alive anymore)
---------------------------------------------

‚Ä®‚Ä®PS Tito is a master at bad drawing. Don‚Äôt expect fine lines with perfect alignment in his drawing (but the colors are fun!).

‚Ä®‚Ä®PPS There‚Äôs no utility in this project except the CC0 license, so just have fun with it ;)‚Ä®‚Ä®

Special thanks to:

Jburn, IndraAziz (Musical Jackal), Binerica, Mirffu (Sigmun) for allowing the making and usage of respective traits
ciphrd and fx(hash) team for allowing the making and usage of fx(hash) traits

metadata.name: The Subversion of Entropy #1
metadata.description:
This project explores the ways in which a highly entropic system can give way to order within chaos. Though composed of many simple primitive shapes, the systems of this project often create a great macro-level structure. These structures, in turn, create a larger composition that seems to be of much lower entropy than the cumulative sum of its often chaotic parts.

Only black and white are used in these compositions, so as to further display the possibilities of a system composed only of simple parts. Notice how the shapes and shades give way to a macro structure that is intertwined with, and defined by, the micro structures present.

Note: display will fill to height of your window, press ‚Äôs‚Äô key to generate a high resolution png. Safari may have some issues, so best viewed on Chrome.
